Q1.1:
STUDY INFORMATION AND INFORMED CONSENT





Project Title: Job Tasks and Abilities Questionnaire

You are being invited to take part in a research study. Before you decide whether to participate it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully. 



What is the purpose of this study?

The aim of this questionnaire is to identify common job tasks that are involved within different sub-divisions of a typical company. We also aim to identify fundamental cognitive abilities necessary to perform these job tasks successfully (e.g., memory, spatial abilities, social abilities etc.) More broadly, we are interested in identifying and safeguarding uniquely human capabilities as AI is becoming increasingly integrated into the workplace.



Do I have to take part?

Taking part is entirely voluntary, and refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future. You are free to withdraw from the experiment at any time without explaining why. 



What will the study involve?

The study involves a questionnaire about the tasks and abilities that are required for your job. The questionnaire should take approximately 20-30 minutes to complete.



Are there any possible disadvantages or risks in taking part?

There are no risks involved in taking part in this questionnaire. There is no time limit, and breaks can be taken as required.



Confidentiality – who will have access to my personal data?

Personally identifiable data will not be made available outside of the study team. We will be using any personal information you give us in order to undertake this study and the University of Cambridge will act as the data controller for this purpose. The legal basis for using your personal information is to carry out a task (i.e. academic research) in the public interest. We will keep identifiable information about you only for as long as necessary for the study. Your rights to access, change or move your information are limited, as we need to manage your information in specific ways in order for the research to be reliable and accurate.  If you withdraw from the study, we will keep the information about you that we have already obtained. To safeguard your rights, we will do our best to only use the minimum personally-identifiable information possible. 

 

For further general information about the University of Cambridge’s use of your personal data as a participant in a research study, please see https://www.information-compliance.admin.cam.ac.uk/data-protection/research-participant-data.



What will happen to the study results?

Results from groups of individuals, without any means of identifying the individuals involved, may be presented at conferences and written up in journals. Non-identifiable data may be shared with other researchers or the public as part of collaborations, joint projects or open access provisions.



Who is organising the research?

The study is organised in the Department of Psychology, University of Cambridge, by Jonathan Prunty. Questions or concerns can be directed to them at jep84@cam.ac.uk. 



Ethics Committee Approval

This project has undergone the review procedure of the Department of Psychology Research Ethics Committee at the University of Cambridge. 



ELECTRONIC CONSENT:

Please indicate whether you agree to take part in this study by selecting one of the two boxes below. Clicking on the “Agree” button indicates that:

	You confirm that you have read and understood the information about the study.
	You understand that your participation is voluntary and that you are free to withdraw at any time, without giving any reason.
	You understand that all personal information will remain confidential and that all efforts will be made to ensure you cannot be identified (except as might be required by law).
	You understand that following open data recommendations the data and findings obtained in this study may be shared with the research community, for example, by uploading the anonymized data file onto an online data depository.
	You confirm that you are at least 18 years of age.
	You agree to take part in the above study.

If you do not wish to participate in this study, please decline participation by clicking on the "Disagree" button.

Patient Data Analysis: I also analyze patient data to track health trends, manage population health, and develop preventive care strategies.

Quality Improvement: I monitor and analyzing quality indicators such as infection rates, patient satisfaction scores, and compliance with healthcare standards to implement quality improvement initiatives.

Operational Efficiency: I examine workflow data and operational processes to enhance efficiency, reduce waste, and streamline procedures.

Resource Allocation: Deciding how to best allocate resources, including staff, equipment, and budget, to optimize operations and meet patient needs.

Crisis Management: Responding to emergencies and unexpected events, such as natural disasters, pandemics, or critical equipment failures, by quickly making decisions to mitigate impact and ensure continuity of care.

Quality Improvement: Identifying areas for improvement in patient care and operational processes, developing solutions, and implementing changes to enhance quality and efficiency.

Conflict Resolution: Addressing conflicts among staff, patients, or between departments, and finding fair and effective resolutions to maintain a positive work environment and ensure patient satisfaction.

Training and Support: Providing training for staff on new technologies and software systems, as well as offering ongoing technical support to ensure effective use of these tools.

Q2.3: I drive a tractor-trailer from our headquarters in Ontario, Canada, delivering freight to all parts of the United States. When the trailer is empty I then pick up freight on my return trip to our headquarters. My specific company has about 80 drivers, but we are only one piece of a larger company. The broad field I work in is Transportation & Logistics.
Q3.7: I made a mistake in choosing my important tasks. I actually do 7 of your listed tasks on a daily basis, but was only asked to pick 5. For example, I occasionally have to unload freight, but not as often as I have to do the other tasks I picked, which is pretty much daily. However my main task is driving. I spend probably 80% of my week doing that, and I should have listed that in the "other" category. I very much need to do the other 5 tasks in order to drive 80% of the time though. It's all part of the job.
1_Q5.1: The first things I need to find out is "where am I going", "how many deliveries do I have" and "when is my first delivery scheduled for"?
5_Q5.1: Sometimes in the course of driving problems will arise that disrupt my schedule such as traffic or bad weather. I might have to decide whether to pull over and shut down if safety becomes and issue. Parking a 70 foot long truck in a safe location is not always an easy thing to do. Sometimes I have to inform my dispatch and the customer that I have decided to delay delivery until the following day because of these reasons.
6_Q5.1: There is a lot of different things that I am required to do in my job. For example I must complete a daily inspection of my truck and trailer each day, and record my findings. Also there is a lot of paperwork i must deal with in regards to multiple Bills of Lading and customs invoices. If I am not organized in how i deal with these things, I can waste a lot of time. I have developed routines for how I handle each specific part of my day in order to minimize wasted time. The less time I spend doing my non-driving activities, the more time I can spend on actual driving, which is the only thing I get paid to do since I am compensated "per mile".
8_Q5.1: The primary way I receive information on how to do my job is through a tablet device. It is connected t-a satellite on my truck, and provides me real-time information on the pickups and deliveries I have to do. It also has a navigation function that will display "truck friendly" routes to get me to my destination safely.  I also communicate with the office using mobile phone and email, but these are less preferred methods. Another vital function this tablet does is it acts as an E-log for my daily activities. (ELD) The government has strict "hours of service" rules that restrict how many hours we can work or drive in a day. This used to be tracked using paper logs, but those could be "manipulated" by the driver. With an ELD this is no longer the case.
9_Q5.1: My communication comes down to two groups of people. My dispatchers back at headquarters who inform me via tablet (and to a lesser degree by phone or email) where or when I have to be somewhere. The second group are clients. Sometimes I have to call them 24 hours ahead of delivery to alert them. Other times I call them if I need specific instructions on how to go about delivering to their location. Of course there is also the face-to-face communication when I arrive at their location for delivery or pick up.

Q2.3: Customer service
3_Q15.1:
Data Collection: Gathering relevant data from various sources, such as sales reports, customer feedback, financial statements, or market research. This can involve pulling data from databases, spreadsheets, or other data management systems.

Data Cleaning: Preparing the data for analysis by removing errors, inconsistencies, and duplicates. This includes standardizing formats, correcting inaccuracies, and ensuring that the data is complete and reliable.

Data Organization: Structuring the data in a way that makes it easier to analyze. This might involve sorting, categorizing, or summarizing the data to identify trends or patterns.

Statistical Analysis: Applying statistical techniques to interpret the data. This includes calculating averages, percentages, and standard deviations, as well as conducting more complex analyses like regression or correlation studies.
5_Q15.1:
Identifying the Problem: Recognizing and clearly defining the issue at hand. This involves gathering information, understanding the context, and pinpointing the root cause of the problem.

Gathering and Analyzing Information: Collecting relevant data and insights from various sources. This includes conducting research, reviewing reports, and consulting with colleagues or experts to understand the problem fully.

Evaluating Options: Weighing different possible solutions by considering their pros and cons. This involves brainstorming potential solutions, assessing their feasibility, and predicting possible outcomes.

Making a Decision: Choosing the best course of action based on the evaluation of options. This includes considering the impact on stakeholders, the resources available, and the alignment with organizational goals.

Implementing the Solution: Putting the chosen solution into action. This involves coordinating with team members, allocating resources, and ensuring everyone understands their roles and responsibilities.

Monitoring and Adjusting: Keeping track of the implementation process to ensure the solution is effective. This includes setting up checkpoints, gathering feedback, and making necessary adjustments to improve the outcome.

Communicating Decisions: Informing relevant stakeholders about the decision and the rationale behind it. This involves clear and transparent communication to ensure everyone is on the same page and can provide support if needed.
6_Q15.1:
1. **Setting Objectives and Goals**: Clearly defining what needs to be achieved within a specific time frame. This involves understanding the project scope and breaking down the overall objectives into manageable tasks.

2. **Prioritizing Tasks**: Determining the importance and urgency of each task to decide the order in which they should be tackled. This helps in focusing on the most critical tasks first.

3. **Creating a Timeline**: Developing a schedule that outlines deadlines for each task or milestone. This ensures that the work progresses in a structured and timely manner.

4. **Resource Allocation**: Identifying and assigning the necessary resources, such as team members, tools, and budget, to each task. This includes coordinating with other departments or external partners if needed.

5. **Developing Work Plans**: Creating detailed plans that outline the steps required to complete each task. This can include creating to-do lists, Gantt charts, or other project management tools to visualize the workflow.

6. **Monitoring Progress**: Regularly checking the status of tasks and comparing them to the timeline and objectives. This helps in identifying any delays or issues early on and making necessary adjustments.

7. **Communication**: Keeping all stakeholders informed about the progress, changes, and any issues that arise. This involves regular meetings, status reports, and updates to ensure everyone is on the same page.

8. **Problem-Solving**: Addressing any obstacles or challenges that arise during the project. This includes brainstorming solutions, making decisions, and adjusting plans as needed to stay on track.

9. **Documentation**: Keeping detailed records of plans, decisions, and progress. This helps in tracking the project’s development and provides a reference for future projects.

10. **Review and Feedback**: After completing the tasks or project, reviewing what went well and what could be improved. Gathering feedback from team members and stakeholders to learn and improve planning for future projects.

These activities are essential for ensuring that work is organized, efficient, and aligned with the overall goals of the project or organization.
8_Q15.1:
Data Entry and Management: Inputting, updating, and managing data in various software applications such as CRM systems, spreadsheets, and databases. This ensures accurate records and efficient retrieval of information when needed.

Communication Tools: Utilizing email, instant messaging, video conferencing, and other communication platforms to stay connected with colleagues, clients, and partners. Tools like Microsoft Teams, Slack, and Zoom are essential for coordinating and collaborating remotely.

Document Creation and Editing: Using word processors, spreadsheets, and presentation software like Microsoft Office or Google Workspace to create, edit, and share documents, reports, and presentations. This includes formatting, proofreading, and ensuring consistency across documents.

Project Management Software: Leveraging tools such as Trello, Asana, or Monday.com to plan, organize, and track the progress of projects. This helps in assigning tasks, setting deadlines, and monitoring the overall workflow.

Research and Information Gathering: Using the internet and specialized databases to conduct research, gather information, and stay updated on industry trends, competitors, and market conditions. This may involve searching for articles, reports, and relevant data.

Technical Troubleshooting: Identifying and resolving technical issues with hardware, software, and network connections. This might include basic troubleshooting steps, coordinating with IT support, or performing regular maintenance tasks.

Software Proficiency: Becoming proficient in industry-specific software or tools that are crucial for job performance. This could include learning new features, attending training sessions, or keeping up with software updates and best practices.

Digital Marketing and Social Media: Using digital marketing tools and social media platforms to promote products or services, engage with audiences, and analyze the effectiveness of marketing campaigns. This includes creating content, scheduling posts, and monitoring analytics.

Cybersecurity Awareness: Following best practices for cybersecurity, such as using strong passwords, recognizing phishing attempts, and ensuring data protection. This helps in safeguarding sensitive information and maintaining the integrity of the company's digital assets.
10_Q15.1:
1. **Networking**: Attending industry events, conferences, and trade shows to meet new contacts and establish connections with potential clients, partners, and colleagues. This also includes participating in online forums and professional social networks like LinkedIn to engage with others in the industry.

2. **Client Engagement**: Regularly communicating with current and prospective clients to understand their needs, provide solutions, and build trust. This involves follow-up calls, emails, and face-to-face meetings to ensure clients feel valued and heard.

3. **Collaborating with Colleagues**: Working closely with team members on projects, sharing knowledge, and offering support. This can include brainstorming sessions, team meetings, and informal catch-ups to foster a collaborative and supportive work environment.

4. **Customer Service**: Providing exceptional customer service by being responsive, helpful, and attentive to client inquiries and issues. This helps in building a positive reputation and long-term relationships with clients.

5. **Building Partnerships**: Identifying and establishing partnerships with other businesses or organizations that can provide mutual benefits. This involves reaching out, negotiating terms, and maintaining ongoing communication to ensure the partnership thrives.

6. **Community Involvement**: Participating in community events, volunteering, or engaging in corporate social responsibility initiatives to build relationships outside the immediate work environment and enhance the company's reputation.

These activities are crucial for creating and maintaining strong, positive relationships with clients, colleagues, and partners, which ultimately contribute to the success and growth of the business.
